image.altText: A tall forward for Collingwood's AFL side roars and pumps his fists in celebration as a teammate comes close.

props.synopsis: Collingwood get on the board early against GWS at the MCG in their preliminary final. Follow live.

title.children: Magpies lead but Giants in range with grand final spot on the line

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: We have got a serious battle on our hands at the MCG tonight. That was mighty impressive from Collingwood. The intensity and physicality around the ball for a minute looked like it was about to overwhelm GWS, and those two early goals set the table for an onslaught. But the Giants held their ground. They haven't quite got to throwing any real punches of their own yet, but they have seen off a serious challenge and remained right in the thick of the game. There were signs late in that quarter that the GWS running game is ready to break free once the heat dies down a little, so the threat remains looming for the Pies. Cracking start, everything you want from a prelim.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: QT: Magpies out to early 11-point lead

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Quick thinking from Crisp, who just slammed it onto the outside of his left boot from an innocuous stoppage inside 50. The Giants didn't have a defender on the line and the ball crept home. Excellent start for Collingwood now.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 16': Jack Crisp out of nowhere! Pies have two!

children.content: Quick thinking from Crisp, who just slammed it onto the outside of his left boot from an innocuous stoppage inside 50.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: No late changes tonight. A big in and a big out for Collingwood, with Nick Daicos playing his first game since round 21 and Taylor Adams missing out due to an injury suffered at training. The Giants are unchanged from the team that beat Port Adelaide last weekend — what a luxury at this stage of the season. The subs are Jack Ginnivan for Collingwood and Xavier O'Halloran for GWS.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: The final teams and subs are in

image.altText: Two rugby league players face off during a match

props.synopsis: Penrith and Melbourne have wasted no time getting started in the first NRL preliminary final. Follow all the updates in our live blog.

title.children: 'Line in the sand' drawn as Panthers and Storm engage in fiery final

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Panthers win a penalty out of their own end - a possible repeat set for the Storm ending up with the Melbourne side being marched back down the field. The Panthers don't need too many chances - and don't need a second invitation. Jarome Luai at first receiver, finds Nathan Cleary, who ghosted away towards his left, delayed the pass before finding Sunia Turuva who finished easily. Cleary converts from the touchline and all of a sudden it's 18-4.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 27' Panthers score again!

children.content: (Getty Images)
The Panthers win a penalty out of their own end - a possible repeat set for the Storm ending up with the Melbourne side being marched back down the field.
The Panthers don't need too many chances - and don't need a second invitation.
Jarome Luai at first receiver, finds Nathan Cleary, who ghosted away towards his left, delayed the pass before finding Sunia Turuva who finished easily.
Cleary converts from the touchline and all of a sudden it's 18-4.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: It's all come from an error by Marion Seve. That gave the Panthers a great field position. The Panthers moved the ball right again, targeting the weak left-edge defence of the Storm and Brian To'o ducked under a couple of would-be tacklers to score in the corner again. Cameron Munster and Justin Olam both drifted a bit left and Dylan Edwards movement right just created the space for him to find Izack Tago, who passed to To'o who did the rest. Cleary makes no mistake this time and gets the extras, Penrith lead 12-4.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 21' Brian To'o has two!

children.content: It's all come from an error by Marion Seve.
That gave the Panthers a great field position.
The Panthers moved the ball right again, targeting the weak left-edge defence of the Storm and Brian To'o ducked under a couple of would-be tacklers to score in the corner again.
(Getty Images)
Cameron Munster and Justin Olam both drifted a bit left and Dylan Edwards movement right just created the space for him to find Izack Tago, who passed to To'o who did the rest.
Cleary makes no mistake this time and gets the extras, Penrith lead 12-4.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext:
Nelson Asofa-Solomona
has smashed Nathan Cleary late after he passed the ball. There is a bit of a stink on after the shot and Adam Gee has a job on his hands here. There was not much in it on second viewing — just a push I think. "The line is in the sand," Gee says. "We just had that down there. It's a push. That's why he's staying on the field. But it's clearly late. If we get any more, I won't hesitate," that's the message for the Storm. "If we keep getting a push and shove. Blokes go," and that's the message for Nathan Cleary. Cleary takes that on board and knocks over the two points to make it 6-4 Penrith.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 16' 'The line is in the sand!'
